Objectives

getting counts for different groups use lubridate to parse dates find confidence intervervals and do t tests heatmap with geom_title()

#Import lobster data

lobster_abundance <- read_csv(here::here("data","lobster_abundance.csv"), 
                              na = "-99999") %>% 
  clean_names()
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   DATE = col_character(),
##   SITE = col_character(),
##   TRANSECT = col_double(),
##   REPLICATE = col_character(),
##   SIZE_MM = col_double(),
##   LOBSTER_COUNT = col_double()
## )

Use tidyr::uncount() funtion to expand a frequency distribution

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>% 
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Now each lobster has its own row, this is tidy format.

Lets look at this in multiple ways:

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color=site), 
              width = 0.2, 
              alpha = 0.3)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_violin(aes(color=site), 
              alpha = 0.3)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(x = size_mm)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = site)) +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(sample = size_mm)) +
  geom_qq(size = 0.5) + 
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_qq).
